SIMPLE: flame
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flame
<hw>Flame</hw> <pr>(fl⟦amac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>flame</ets>, <ets>flaume</ets>, <ets>flaumbe</ets>, OF.
<ets>flame</ets>, <ets>flambe</ets>, F. <ets>flamme</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>flamma</ets>, fr. <ets>flamma</ets>, fr. <ets>flagrare</ets> to
burn. See <er>Flagrant</er>, and cf. <er>Flamneau</er>,
<er>Flamingo</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A stream of burning vapor or
gas, emitting light and heat; darting or streaming fire; a blaze; a
fire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Burning zeal or passion; elevated and noble
enthusiasm; glowing imagination; passionate excitement or anger.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧In a <xex>flame</xex> of zeal severe.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where <qex>flames</qex> refin'd in breasts seraphic glow.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Smit with the love of sister arts we came,⟦br⟧
And met congenial, mingling <qex>flame</qex> with <qex>flame</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Ardor of affection; the passion of love.</def>
<rj><au>Coleridge.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A person beloved; a sweetheart.</def>
<rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Blaze; brightness; ardor. See
<er>Blaze</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Flame bridge</b></col>, <cd>a bridge wall. See
<er>Bridge</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 5.</cd> -- <col><b>Flame
color</b></col>, <cd>brilliant orange or yellow.</cd> <au>B.
Jonson.</au> -- <col><b>Flame engine</b></col>, <cd>an early name for
the gas engine.</cd> -- <col><b>Flame manometer</b></col>, <cd>an
instrument, invented by Koenig, to obtain graphic representation of the
action of the human vocal organs. See <er>Manometer</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Flame reaction</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a method of
testing for the presence of certain elements by the characteristic color
imparted to a flame; as, sodium colors a flame yellow, potassium violet,
lithium crimson, boracic acid green, etc. Cf. <cref>Spectrum
analysis</cref>, under <er>Spectrum</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Flame
tree</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a tree with showy scarlet flowers,
as the <spn>Rhododendron arboreum</spn> in India, and the
<spn>Brachychiton acerifolium</spn> of Australia.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flame</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flame
<hw>Flame</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Flamed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Flaming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>flamen</ets>,
<ets>flaumben</ets>, F. <ets>flamber</ets>, OF. also, <ets>flamer</ets>.
See <er>Flame</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To burn with a
flame or blaze; to burn as gas emitted from bodies in combustion; to
blaze.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The main blaze of it is past, but a small thing would make it
<qex>flame</qex> again.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To burst forth like flame; to break out in violence
of passion; to be kindled with zeal or ardor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>flamed</qex> with indignation.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flame</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flame
<hw>Flame</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To kindle; to inflame; to
excite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>flamed</qex> with zeal of vengeance inwardly.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flame-colored</ent>⟦br⟧
